bib.title: Experimental investigation of charge symmetry breaking effects in the reaction 4He(d,3He)3H between Ed=32 and 50 MeV.

free_txt: Detector telescopes (four telescopes
simultaneously) in the scattering chamber were mounted
on two turnable segments which can be rotated
independently around the target in order to measure the
angular distributions. Telescopes with three silicon
surface barrier detectors are used to discriminate
these particles from protons, deuterons and 4He. The
two first detectors in coincidence give dE and E
proportional signals for the 3He and 4He nucleus. The
second and third detectors give the corresponding
signals for the hydrogen-isotopes tritons,deuterons and
protons. For Ed=40 MeV the following detector
thicknesses were used; for the first telescope in the
angular range ANG1=10 degr. to 30 degr. they were 100
mu-m,500 mu-m and 1000 mu-m. The second telescope
covering the angular range ANG2=25 degr. to 45degr. was
equipped with detectors 75 mu-m, 300 mu-m and 1000 mu-m
thick.

For the present polarization data an overall absolute
calibration uncertainty of 2% is estimated at energies
below 40 MeV and 3% at 45 and 50 MeV due to the error
propagation inherent to the energy degrading method.
The statistical accuracy ranges from 0.005 to 0.010.
Besides the statistical error, which is for all
data points smaller than 1%,a general independent error
of 1% was attributed to the data due to systematic
error arising.
Deuteron beam was calibrated using elastic d(a,a)
scattering at the energy range Ed=17 to 43 MeV.
The gas cell,32 mm in diameter,has 6.3 mu-m thick Havar
entrance and exit windows and was filled with 800 Torr
4He. For angles smaller than 10 degr. there was used an
elongated target 0f 60 mm length in the beam direction
and 24 mm wide,equipped with a 6.3 mu-m thick entrance
window and a 12.6 mu-m thick Havar exit window.
